1Ô∏è‚É£ What is Page Caching? (Exact definition)

Page caching means caching the entire HTML response of a page and serving it directly from the web server without hitting Rails at all.

No:

controller

model

view

database

Rails is completely bypassed.

2Ô∏è‚É£ How Page Caching Works (conceptually)
First request:

Request comes to Rails

Controller action runs

View renders HTML

HTML is saved as a static file

Response is returned

Next request:

Request comes in

Web server (Nginx/Apache) finds cached HTML

HTML is returned directly

Rails never runs

3Ô∏è‚É£ Simple Example (Blog posts page)

Route:

GET /posts


Controller:

class PostsController < ApplicationController
  def index
    @posts = Post.all
  end
end

Cached result:
public/posts.html


Now:

Visiting /posts

Server returns posts.html

Rails is skipped entirely üöÄ

4Ô∏è‚É£ Why Page Caching Is FAST
Step	Fragment caching	Page caching
Rails boot	‚úÖ Yes	‚ùå No
Controller	‚úÖ Yes	‚ùå No
View rendering	Partial	‚ùå No
DB queries	Often	‚ùå No
Web server only	‚ùå	‚úÖ

üëâ Fastest possible caching

5Ô∏è‚É£ Why Rails Removed Built-in Page Caching

Page caching was removed after Rails 3 because:

‚ùå No user-specific content
‚ùå Hard to expire
‚ùå Doesn‚Äôt work well with auth / sessions
‚ùå Breaks dynamic pages

So Rails moved to:

HTTP caching

Reverse proxy caching

Fragment caching

6Ô∏è‚É£ Modern Rails Page Caching (How it‚Äôs done now)

Instead of Rails doing it, we use:

üîπ Nginx / Varnish / Cloudflare

Rails sends headers:

expires_in 10.minutes, public: true


Web server / CDN caches the full page.

7Ô∏è‚É£ Page Caching vs Fragment Caching
Feature	Page caching	Fragment caching
Cached content	Entire page HTML	Part of page
Rails involved	‚ùå No	‚úÖ Yes
Per-user content	‚ùå No	‚úÖ Yes
Speed	üöÄ Fastest	Fast
Flexibility	Low	High
8Ô∏è‚É£ When to Use Page Caching

‚úÖ Public pages
‚úÖ Same content for everyone
‚úÖ Rarely changing pages

Examples:

Landing pages

Marketing pages

Blogs (public view)

Documentation

9Ô∏è‚É£ When NOT to Use Page Caching

‚ùå Logged-in pages
‚ùå Personalized dashboards
‚ùå Pages with sessions / cookies
‚ùå Admin panels

10Ô∏è‚É£ One-Line Interview Answer

Page caching stores the entire rendered HTML of a page and serves it directly from the web server, completely bypassing Rails for maximum performance.

Mental model

Fragment caching = cache parts
Russian doll = cache parts + container
Page caching = cache everything